<l:h1>The western front:<l:/h1>
In August, the five German armies invaded Belgium and thereafter France. They intended to beat the Frenchmen in 6 weeks, and then turn to the eastern front to fight the Russians.
The German invasion did not go as planned, because the Belgian army fought bravely and was able to delay the German armies. At the battle at Mons, a small English army force was able to delay the German 1st Army. This gave the Frenchmen the possibility to reestablish their army at river Marne northeast of Paris. A few days earlier, the Frenchmen had been badly beaten at Lorraine.
The battle at Marne lasted for five days, and more than two million men fought along the 240 kilometer front. Finally the Germans pulled 60 kilometers back to the river Aisne. Here, their army entrenched and established machine gun nests. Soon the trenches ran 760 kilometers from the Flanders in Belgium to Switzerland.
